{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:38:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:38:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12875"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12875"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.84,0.07,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52113"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5317"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37431"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1866"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"50016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52113"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother. Through an interpreter, it is learned that for the past two days, the infant has had fever, runny nose, red watery eyes, frequent coughing, and a rash across his body. He has also been having frequent diarrhoea. The family are refugees from a war-torn country, and the mother reports that her son has never received any vaccinations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the infant appears unwell. His pulse rate is 155/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 65/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 39.0\u00b0C. There is a maculopapular rash across the torso, arms, and legs. The oral mucosa shows red and white spots resembling grains of salt on the buccal surface.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mumps","Measles","Rubella","Infectious mononucleosis","Varicella"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasles\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnvaccinated status, which significantly increases the risk for measles, a highly communicable disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECharacteristic symptoms: fever, coryza (runny nose), conjunctivitis (red, watery eyes), cough, and a maculopapular rash across the body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKoplik\u0027s spots: the red and white spots in the mouth, resembling grains of salt, are pathognomonic for measles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplications: the infant is showing signs of severe complications including diarrhoea and respiratory distress (elevated respiratory rate and low oxygen saturation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMumps\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, headache, myalgia, and characteristic parotid gland swelling, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubella\u003C/strong\u003E, while sharing some symptoms with measles, typically causes a milder illness. The rash in rubella is often less extensive, and Koplik\u0027s spots are not a feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious mononucleosis\u003C/strong\u003E usually affects older children and young adults. It typically presents with sore throat, lymphadenopathy, and hepatosplenomegaly, which are not described in this infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella\u003C/strong\u003E (chickenpox) presents with a characteristic vesicular rash that progresses from macules to papules to vesicles to crusts. The rash in this case is described as maculopapular, which is more consistent with measles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical presentation and the patient\u0027s unvaccinated status, measles is the most likely diagnosis. This case highlights the importance of recognising the clinical signs of measles, as it is a highly infectious and potentially lethal infection, especially in young children. Prompt diagnosis and management are crucial to prevent complications and limit spread.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Measles typically presents with fever, coryza, conjunctivitis, cough, and a characteristic maculopapular rash in unvaccinated individuals.","Koplik\u0027s spots, appearing as white lesions on a red background on the buccal mucosa, are pathognomonic for measles.","Complications of measles can include pneumonia and diarrhoea, which can be severe in young children."],"references":["Batirel, A., \u0026 Doganay, M. 2013. Clinical approach to skin eruption and measles: a mini review. J Gen Pract, 1(118), 2. Available from: 10.4172/2329-9126.1000118","White, S. J., Boldt, K. L., Holditch, S. J., Poland, G. A., \u0026 Jacobson, R. M. 2012. Measles, mumps, and rubella. Clinical obstetrics and gynecology, 55(2), 550. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3334858/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevisi